  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Ghana Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (GWASH) Project</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Ghana Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (GWASH) Project is an innovative project that supports efforts by other development partners to scale up access to improved water and sanitation infrastructures for the not-served and underserved population as well as promote the adoption of complementary hygiene practices. The long-term goal of the Ghana WASH Project is to maximize health impacts in the project areas. In terms of water infrastructure, the project exceeded by 87% of its target, and reached 112,500 people through the construction/rehabilitation of 79 boreholes, 38 hand dug wells, 2 water pipe systems, and 11 surface water kiosks. As for the sanitation infrastructure, the GWASH project also exceeded its targets by constructing a total of 5,525 latrines.  The project build the capacities of LNGOs, WatSan Committees, teachers, food vendors, and many other beneficiary groups. Additionally, RI trained 78,387 people in behavior change and hygiene messages. RI collaborated and developed partnerships with local and international private sector partners and continued to support the implementation of project activities already established with PPP agreements.</narrative>
  </description>
